            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">ir-Rūḥīya is a town and municipality in the <ref target="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siliana_Governorate"><hi rendition="#u">Silyǟ</hi><hi rendition="#u">na Go</hi><hi rendition="#u">u</hi><hi rendition="#u">vernorate</hi></ref>. In 2004, it counted 4.307 inhabitants. Its original population was formed by the Arabic tribes Ūlǟd Mǟžir and Ūlǟd ʕAyyār. It includes several districts (is-Smīrǟt, Findig Dibbīš, Bū ʕAžīla, is-Skārna, la-Ḥmayma,…). Due to its location in the transition area of three Gouvernorates, it used to belong to il-Kǟf first, later became a part of il-Gaṣrīn and as Silyǟna became a Gouvernorate of its own, it became a part of Silyǟna. Inside of ir-Rūḥīya the dialect of Skārna is famous for its unique expressions. It is told, that the name of the town is derived from “<hi rendition="#i">ar-rūḥ h</hi><hi rendition="#i">ī</hi><hi rendition="#i">ya</hi>”. ir-Rūḥīya used to be a vivid center of spiritual life, famous for its <hi rendition="#i">zrid</hi>-ceremonies, where the local population as well as people from other parts of Tunisia regularly visited the saints tombs (f.e. Umm id-Dlǟl, Sīdi l-Hēdi, Ḥmid Bū ʕĪn, Sīdi ʕAlī). After the revolution in 2011 these activities stopped and are now slowly coming back in the last years.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
